content.problemStatement:
A parameterized constructor in Java allows you to pass specific values when creating an object. This lets you initialize object fields with custom values at the time of object creation.
- It has the `same name as the class`.
- It doesn't have a `return type` (not even void).
- It can take one or more `parameters`.

**Syntax:**
```java
class ClassName {
    public ClassName(dataType parameter1, dataType parameter2) {
        // Initialize fields with parameters
    }
}
```
---

**Example:**
```java
class Seedit {
    String name;  // Attribute to store student's name
    int grade;    // Attribute to store student's grade

    // Constructor to initialize the name and grade
    SEED-IT(String studentName, int studentGrade) {
        name = studentName;  // Assign the given name
        grade = studentGrade; // Assign the given grade
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Create a Codechef object (Student object) with parameterized constructor
        SEED-IT student1 = new SEED-IT("Raj", 69);  // John’s details

        // Displaying the student's name and grade directly inside main method
        System.out.println(student1.name + "'s Grade: " + student1.grade);  // John’s grade
    }
}

```
**Expected Output:**
```default
Raj Grade: 69
```

